as the name of the first of Christ's disciples, the patron saint of both Scotland and Russia. The Scottish surname   Anderson   is far more common than its Russian equivalent, <b>Andreev</b>. The personal name was popular throughout Europe in various vernacular forms (including Italian <i>Andrea</i>, French <i>André</i>, Spanish <i>Andrés</i>, Scottish, North German, and Scandinavian <i>Anders</i>, Dutch <i>Andries</i>, Hungarian <i>András</i>, Czech <i>Ondřej</i>, Polish <i>Andrzej</i> and <i>Jędrzej</i>, and Russian <i>Andrey</i>).","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Andrejaš</b>: from an old vernacular form of the personal name <i>Andraž</i> (from Latin <i>Andreas</i>), which is a variant of <i>Andrej</i>; see   Andrew  ."]}]},{"name":"Arnaud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>Arnold</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Arnaud I d'Andres Viscount of Marchiennes was born before 1115, in Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, his father, Viscount Elembert de Marcq, was 25 and his mother, Adele Licques, was 20. He married Gertrude Gent. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1136, and was buried in Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France."},"et":{"before 1115–Aft 1136":"enne 1115–pärast 1136","1115–1136":"1115–1136","1120–1176":"1120–1176","1082–1138":"1082–1138","1125–1148":"1125–1148","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","1095–Female":"1095–Surnud","Aft 1136":"pärast 1136","1090":"1090","before 1115":"enne 1115","1176":"1176","1120":"1120","Abt 1125":"umbes 1125","1095":"1095","1082":"1082","1139":"1139","1138":"1138","1148":"1148","1115":"1115","1125":"1125","1136":"1136","France":"Prantsusmaa","Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Frankrijk":"Ardres, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsu